<p><b>0</b> (<b>zero</b>) is both a <a href="/wiki/Number" title="Number">number</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Numerical_digit" title="Numerical digit">numerical digit</a> used to represent that number in <a href="/wiki/Numeral_system" title="Numeral system">numerals</a>. It plays a central role in <a href="/wiki/Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics</a> as the <a href="/wiki/Additive_identity" title="Additive identity">additive identity</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Integer" title="Integer">integers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Real_number" title="Real number">real numbers</a>, and many other <a href="/wiki/Algebra" title="Algebra">algebraic</a> structures. As a digit, zero is used as a placeholder in <a href="/wiki/Positional_notation" title="Positional notation">place value systems</a>. In the <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English language</a>, zero may also be called <b>oh</b>, <b>null</b>, <b>nil</b>, <b>zilch</b><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>, <b>zip</b>, or <b>naught</b>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
